]]\n| ''[[Misery (film)|Misery]]'' (1990)\n|-\n| ''[[Miss Lonelyhearts]]'' (1933), [[Nathanael West]]\n| ''[[Miss Lonelyhearts#Film, TV or theatrical adaptations \u2013 1933 film|Advice to the Lovelorn]]'' (1933)<br />''[[Lonelyhearts]]'' (1958)<br />''[[Miss Lonelyhearts#Film, TV or theatrical adaptations \u2013 1983 film|Miss Lonelyhearts]]'' (1983) (TV)\n|-\n| ''[[Moby-Dick]]'' (1851), [[Herman Melville]]\n| ''[[The Sea Beast]]'' (1926)<br/>''[[Moby Dick (1956 film)|Moby Dick]]'' (1956)<br />''[[Tom and Jerry]] in: [[Dicky Moe]]'' (1962)<br />''[[Moby Dick (1978 film)|Moby Dick]]'' (1978)<br />''[[Dot and the Whale]]'' (1986)<br />''[[Adaptations of Moby-Dick#Moby Dick, a 1998 television film starring Patrick Stewart as Ahab and Gregory Peck as Father Mapple (a Golden Globe-winning performance)|Moby Dick]]'' (1998) (TV)<br />''[[Adaptations of Moby-Dick#In 1999, a 25-minute paint-on-glass-animated adaptation was made by the Russian studio Man and Time, directed by Natalya Orlova. It was made for the British market, and so was in English. Rod Steiger was the voice of Captain Ahab. The film came in third place at the 5th Open Russian Festival of Animated Film.|Moby Dick]]'' (1999)<br />''[[Capitaine Achab]]'' (2004)<br />''[[Moby Dick (2010 film)|Moby Dick]]'' (2010)<br />''[[Adaptations of Moby-Dick#Moby Dick, a 2010 television mini series directed by Mike Barker, starring William Hurt as Ahab and Ethan Hawke as Starbuck.|Moby Dick]]'' (2010) (TV) (mini)<br />''[[Adaptations of Moby-Dick#Moby Dick, a 2011 television film for Syfy that was apparently so bad, in its revisionistic update of the novel, that it did not even get the customary re-run at 1:00 A.M. the night of its debut!|Moby Dick]]'' (2011) (TV)<br />''[[Age of the Dragons]]'' (2011)\n|-\n| ''[[Moderato Cantabile]]'' (1958), [[Marguerite Duras]]\n| ''[[Seven Days... Seven Nights]]'' (1960)\n|-\n| ''The Molly Maguires'' (1969), Arthur H. Lewis\n| ''[[The Molly Maguires (film)|The Molly Maguires]]'' (1970)